hands_on_practices.introduction:
The concept of the Lie derivative extends beyond vector fields to describe how any tensor field changes along the flow of a vector field. This practice shifts our focus to a type-(0,2) tensor, which could represent physical quantities like a metric tensor or a stress-energy tensor. You will calculate the Lie derivative of a simple diagonal tensor field, which reveals how the rotational flow generated by the vector field $X$ deforms the tensor, even though its components are constant. This exercise illustrates the general formula for the Lie derivative of a tensor, $(\mathcal{L}_X T)_{ij} = X^k 
abla_k T_{ij} + T_{kj} 
abla_i X^k + T_{ik} 
abla_j X^k$, and provides insight into how geometric symmetries affect physical fields [@problem_id:1535913].
